  "prompt": "Is it likely that stem cell tooth regeneration will be possible by next year (2017)?",
  "response": "By 2017, it was unlikely that fully developed stem cell tooth regeneration treatments would be available to the general public. Research into using stem cells for tooth regeneration has been ongoing for several years, with promising results in laboratory and animal studies. However, translating these findings into safe and effective treatments for humans involves significant challenges, including regulatory approvals, ensuring the safety and efficacy of the procedures, and developing reliable clinical protocols.\n\nAs of now, while there have been advancements in regenerative dentistry, fully functional and widely available stem cell-based tooth regeneration treatments are not yet a reality. The timeline for such innovations reaching clinical practice and becoming accessible to patients often extends over several years or even decades, considering the complexities involved in medical research and development.",
